{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17575407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17575407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T02:38:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T02:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1216"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1216"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.12,0.17,0.44,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1216"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98443"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46098"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice on his cardiovascular mortality risk. His family history is unknown. He has no symptoms suggestive of coronary artery or peripheral vascular disease. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and quit eight years ago. His medical history is significant for hypertension, for which he takes perindopril. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 138/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His BMI is 29 kg/m\u00b2. Cardiovascular examination is unremarkable. Recent lipid studies reveal a total cholesterol of 5.8 mmol/L (3.9-5.5) and a high-density lipoprotein cholesterol of 1.1 mmol/L (\u0026gt;1.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on this information, this patient scores at 9% (intermediate risk) on the Australian Cardiovascular Disease Risk calculator. He remains concerned as his family history is unknown, and asks if there are further tests that can assist with stratifying his cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to consider next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electrocardiogram","Exercise stress electrocardiogram","Exercise stress echocardiogram","Coronary artery calcium score","CT coronary angiogram"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with intermediate cardiovascular risk (9%) based on the Australian Cardiovascular Disease Risk calculator and is seeking further risk stratification. According to Australian guidelines, coronary artery calcium (CAC) scoring is recommended when the calculated cardiovascular risk is intermediate and treatment decisions remain uncertain or further risk stratification is requested before committing to life long primary prevention therapies. CAC scoring may help reclassify risk when additional risk factors not captured by the calculator are present, or when further information would help inform shared decision-making about therapy. It is important to note that CAC scoring is not recommended for generalised population screening, but can be considered for selected patients like this one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery calcium score\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation for cardiovascular risk stratification in this asymptomatic patient. CAC scoring uses non-contrast CT to detect calcified plaque, which is highly specific for atherosclerosis. It provides a direct measure of atherosclerotic burden and has been shown to improve risk prediction beyond traditional risk factors. A CAC score of zero is associated with very low cardiovascular risk, while higher scores correlate with increased risk. This information can help guide decisions about preventive treatments such as statin therapy. CAC scoring is non-invasive, does not require contrast, and has lower radiation exposure than CT coronary angiography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT coronary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E provides more comprehensive anatomical detail including both calcified and non-calcified plaque, as well as the degree of luminal stenosis. However, it is not a first-line test for risk stratification in asymptomatic individuals. It requires intravenous contrast, has higher radiation exposure, and is more expensive than CAC scoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is a basic cardiac investigation that can detect rhythm abnormalities and signs of previous myocardial infarction or left ventricular hypertrophy. However, in asymptomatic individuals, a resting ECG has very low sensitivity for detecting subclinical coronary artery disease and is not useful for risk stratification beyond what is already captured in standard risk calculators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercise stress electrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise stress echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E are functional tests that can detect inducible myocardial ischaemia. However, they are not recommended for screening asymptomatic individuals, even those at intermediate risk. These tests have limited sensitivity and specificity in asymptomatic populations and may lead to unnecessary downstream testing. They are more appropriately used in patients with symptoms suggestive of coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coronary artery calcium (CAC) scoring may be considered for risk reclassification when calculated cardiovascular risk is intermediate and treatment decisions remain uncertain.","CAC scoring uses non-contrast CT to detect calcified plaque and can help guide shared decision-making about preventive treatments in asymptomatic patients.","CAC scoring is not recommended for generalised population screening but is appropriate for selected patients with intermediate risk where additional information would aid clinical decision-making."],"references":["Chua A, Blankstein R, Ko B. Coronary artery calcium in primary prevention. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 Aug;49(8):464-469.","Liew et al, 2017, \u2018Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand Position Statement: Coronary Artery Calcium Scoring\u2019, Heart, Lung and Circulation, vol. 26, no. 12, pp. 1239\u20131251.","Lennings et al, 2021, \u0027National Heart Foundation of Australia: position statement on coronary artery calcium scoring for the primary prevention of cardiovascular disease in Australia\u0027, Med J Aust, vol. 214, no. 9, pp. 434-439.","Nelson MR, Banks E, Brown A, Chow CK, Peiris DP, Stocks NP, Davies Ao R, Raffoul N, Kalman L, Bradburn E, Jennings G. 2023 Australian guideline for assessing and managing cardiovascular disease risk. Med J Aust. 2024 May 20;220(9):482-490. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2024/220/9/2023-australian-guideline-assessing-and-managing-cardio..."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98443"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1216"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98443"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1216"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116444"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position